				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_{\text {T}}^{\text {miss}}$$\end{document} modelling, the numbers of events in the CRs and the tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}$$\end{document} theoretical uncertainties.

Theory uncertainties in the signal acceptance are taken into account. These are computed by varying the strong coupling constant αs\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha _{s}$$\end{document}, the renormalization and factorization scales, the CKKW scale used to match the parton shower and matrix element descriptions and the parton shower tunes. These uncertainties are mostly relevant for the four-body selection and range between 10% and 30% depending on the mass difference mt~1-mχ~10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
